{"hypothesis_id": "HD1", "rev": 30, "ts": "2026-05-18T11:05:00Z", "statement": "DIAGNOSTIC RESULT (rev29 learning-curve, run lcurve-20260518-104527; LTC-USDT-PERP H180 L64 D4 seed0, 120 epochs, NO early-stop, exact frozen core+_build_tcn, persisted f32 cache). Under-training hypothesis REFUTED -- the rev25/rev28 'refuted' verdict is ROBUST (now better explained). Curve: train_loss collapses monotonically 0.696->0.082 (model HAS capacity to fit/memorize train); val_logloss EXPLODES 0.6916->1.846 (corr(ep,val_ll)=+0.95), min 0.6914 at epoch 3 then diverges far above no-skill ln2~0.6931; OOS test_ric peaks TRIVIALLY EARLY (+0.0131@ep2, +0.0111@ep3 -- within the ~0.004 seed-noise floor and far below the LTC-H180 baseline_ref 0.0378), then decays to ~0/slightly negative and stays (mean -0.0022, min -0.0092, final -0.0015@ep120; corr(ep,test_ric)=+0.19 i.e. no improvement with training). CONCLUSION: the model is NOT under-trained -- it OVERFITS within ~3 epochs (textbook train-down/val-up); training 15x longer than the rev25 effective stop does NOT rescue OOS skill, it destroys it. The user's 'stopped too early while still improving' hypothesis is the OPPOSITE of what occurs; the negative stands stronger (robust to removing early-stop). select!=judge IS real and now quantified: at the val-optimum (ep3) val_ric=+0.0355 vs test_ric=+0.0111 (val ~3x optimistic); rev25 logloss-stop lands ep8 (test_ric -0.0071, late vs the ep3 val-optimum, not early). BUT even the best-possible checkpoint by ANY rule (cherry-pick best test_ric +0.0131@ep2) is within noise and sub-baseline -> no selection rule would have changed HD1-seq's refuted outcome. IMPLICATION for the rev29 locked design: (i) under-training confound RULED OUT (negative trustworthy); (ii) the select-on-val-skill + larger-patience fix remains justified for GENERAL future TCN-arch work but is NECESSARY-NOT-SUFFICIENT; (iii) the real bottleneck is OVERFIT-ON-NOISE at ~16k train rows, not training duration -> future TCN-arch 